				<p>The dieting world is ever-changing, and it's hard to keep track of all the diets out there. Additionally, not all diets are effective for weight loss. Some simply are just fad diets. But, intermittent fasting isn't one of your fad diets. In recent years, it has become one of the most popular diets out there. It not only helps you reduce weight but also improves your overall health. So what exactly is an Intermittent Fasting Diet? </p>
				<!--<h3>The most common signs of poor gut health are:</h3>-->
				<h3>What is Intermittent Fasting? </h3>
				<p>Firstly, you might be surprised to know that intermittent fasting isn't exactly a diet; it's an eating pattern. The diet/eating pattern doesn't change <strong>what</strong> you eat but focuses on <strong>when</strong> you eat. There are several intermittent fasting methods, but the most common method is 16:8 or 24 hours fasting, twice a week.</p>
<p>Fasting isn't new to Indians. Our rishis and ancestors had been fasting for years. It has modified our bodies and allowed us to function well without food for extended hours. 

</p>
				<h3>Types of intermittent fasting</h3>
				<p><strong>16:8 method:</strong> This is one of the most popular methods of intermittent fasting. The method involves fasting for 16 hours and eating within the 8 hours window. Most people who follow this method skip breakfast and eat during 1â€“9 pm. You can usually fit in 2-3 meals within the 8-hour eating window. This method can seem difficult for people who love breakfast. However, you can drink water, coffee, zero-cal beverages, and tea during your 16-hour fasting window. </p> 
<p><strong>5:2 diet:</strong> The 5:2 method doesn't restrict your eating hours for 5 days of the week. You can practically eat everything that you eat daily during those 5 days. But for the remaining 2 days, your daily calorie intake is restricted to 500-600 calories. For example, you can generally eat every day apart from Tuesday and Friday. On those days, women can eat 2 small meals 250 calories each, and men can eat 2 small meals 300 calories each. </p>

<p><strong>Eat-Stop-Eat:</strong> As the name suggests, you can usually eat every day but fast for 24 hours once or twice a week. For example, you can fast after your 7 pm Thursday meal to 7 pm Friday. Depending on your schedule, you can also fast breakfast to breakfast or lunch to lunch. Drink water, coffee, zero-calorie drinks, and tea are allowed during the fasting hours. Fasting for 24-hours could be challenging for many people out there. </p>

<p><strong>Warrior diet:</strong> Warrior diet slightly alters what you eat throughout the day. People using the warrior diet usually eat small amounts of raw fruits and vegetables during the week and eat one big meal at night. Though you can eat anything for your huge dinner meal, unprocessed, healthy, and natural food is usually recommended. 
