				<h3>Benefits of intermittent fasting</h3>
				<p><strong>Weight Loss:</strong> For many, the reason for giving intermittent fasting a shot is weight loss. In a short period, many studies have anchored that intermittent fasting helps weight loss. Through this method, you end up eating fewer calories than usual. Of course, that's considering you are eating somewhat healthy during the non-fasting window.  

<p><strong>Reduce Inflammation:</strong> Several studies have shown that fasting reduces inflammation in our bodies. During fasting, pro-inflammatory markers are present at a lower level than usual, and the same can be said about blood pressure, body weight, and body fat. </p>

<p><strong>Improves Hormone and Cell Function:</strong> Fasting can cause several changes in your body. During fasting periods, your levels of insulin drop significantly, which helps burn fat faster. Intermittent fasting can also increase your human growth hormone levels (HGH), helping burn fat more quickly and increase muscle gain. </p>

<p><strong>Benefits For the Brain:</strong> Intermittent fasting increases your metabolic rate, which is indirectly vital for your brain. Brain hormone BNF is increased during intermittent fasting. IF also helps the growth of new nerve cells. Several studies have also shown that IF reduces the risk of neurological disorders like Alzheimer's disease, Parkinson's disease, and stroke. </p>

<p><strong>Reduce Insulin Resistance:</strong> Intermittent fasting resets insulin levels and stabilizes blood sugar levels for people with diabetes. During IF, the calorie intake of a person reduces and eventually improves insulin resistance.</p>

<p><strong>Increased Cell Turnover:</strong> Fasting gives a break to your body and gives it a chance to self-heal and repair. Intermittent fasting helps with autophagy, which is a process where cells digest and remove old and non-functional proteins in our cells. It will also get rid of old and damaged cells that may accelerate aging.</p>

				<h3>Final Thought:</h3>

<p>Intermittent fasting is one of the most popular diets out there. While it's an excellent diet for weight loss, it may not be for everyone. 'IF' goes beyond weight loss. It helps you live a better, healthier, and longer life. Just like we give a break to ourselves for working hard throughout the week, it's safe to say that our body also needs rest every once in a while. However, with all its benefits, this diet should be avoided by people with eating disorders. People with diabetes or heart conditions should also talk to their dietician before starting the diet. 
